'''''Kaleidoscope Dream''''' is the second [[studio album]] by American [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] recording artist [[Miguel (singer)|Miguel]], released on September 25, 2012, by [[RCA Records]]. After attaining commercial standing with his 2010 debut album ''[[All I Want Is You (album)|All I Want Is You]]'', Miguel wanted to play a larger creative role in his music and principally produced and wrote ''Kaleidoscope Dream''. He recorded most of the album at [[Platinum Sound Recording Studios]] in New York City and MJP Studios in Los Angeles, and worked with producers [[Oak (producer)|Warren "Oak" Felder]], [[Jerry Duplessis|Jerry "Wonda" Duplessis]], and [[Salaam Remi]], among others.

An idiosyncratic album, ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' features sparse production, eccentric details, and hazy, reverbed sounds. Its music incorporates R&B, [[pop music|pop]], [[funk]], [[rock music|rock]], and [[soul music|soul]] styles, as well as [[electronic music|electronic]] flourishes, [[psychedelic music|psychedelic]] textures, and [[funk rock]] guitar. Lyrically, the album generally discusses sexual and romantic themes, with existential subject matter on some songs. Miguel titled ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' as a metaphor for life and sought to represent his own lifestyle and personality with its music and lyrics.

Prior to its release, the album's songs were previewed [[viral marketing|virally]] through a series of free [[music download|digital]] [[extended play|EPs]] released by Miguel. It was subsequently promoted with two singles, including Miguel's highest charting single "[[Adorn (song)|Adorn]]", and his touring in North America and Europe during 2012 to 2013. Upon its release, ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' received rave reviews from music critics, who praised its eccentric style and Miguel's singing and songwriting. It debuted at number three on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 71,000 copies in its first week. As of November 14, 2012, the album has sold 169,600 copies in the United States.

== Background ==
After having it shelved by [[Jive Records]] for two years, Miguel released his debut album ''[[All I Want Is You (album)|All I Want Is You]]'' in November 2010.<ref name="Rytlewski">{{cite news|last=Rytlewski|first=Evan|date=October 9, 2012|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/miguel-kaleidoscope-dream,86389/|title=Miguel: Kaleidoscope Dream|journal=[[The A.V. Club]]|location=Chicago|accessdate=October 19, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhNoDksf|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> It initially performed poorly and was underpromoted by Jive,<ref name="Rytlewski"/> amid the label's dissolution.<ref name="McCarthy">{{cite web|last=McCarthy|first=Sean|date=October 19, 2012|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/164313-miguel-kaleidoscope-dream/|title=Miguel: Kaleidoscope Dream|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=October 20, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhNyQf5A|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> However, as its singles attained radio airplay and Miguel toured in its promotion,<ref name="Lipshutz">{{cite journal|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|date=September 21, 2012|url=http://www.billboard.com/features/miguel-s-kaleidoscope-dream-inside-the-r-1007955262.story|title=Miguel's 'Kaleidoscope Dream': Inside The R&B Dynamo's Fresh Start|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=October 20, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhO2d9mt|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> the album became a [[sleeper hit]] and helped him garner an audience and commercial standing.<ref name="Rytlewski"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Graham|first=Nadine|date=March 24, 2011|url=http://soultrain.com/2011/03/24/qa-miguel/|title=Q&A: Miguel|publisher=[[Soul Train]]|accessdate=October 17, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhO4r8Ai|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> He also garnered a following with his fervent concert performances.<ref name="Kennedy">{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=Gerrick D.|date=November 11, 2012|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-rb-renaissance-miguel-20121111,0,3483680.story|title=Miguel helps lead the charge for an edgier kind of R&B artist|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=November 10, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6C5Kwb0YH|archivedate=November 10, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> After Jive was shut down and absorbed by [[RCA Records]], Miguel acquired a new marketing team to develop himself as more than a "typical R&B artist".<ref name="Lipshutz"/> 

With ''Kaleidoscope Dream'', he sought to reintroduce himself artistically,<ref name="Lipshutz"/> having felt pigeonholed into being marketed as an [[urban contemporary|urban]] artist with Jive,<ref name="Cooper"/> and was inspired by his "more alternative" musical influences.<ref name="RTT">{{cite web|date=October 7, 2012|url=http://www.rttnews.com/1978561/miguel-releases-the-thrill-video.aspx|title=Miguel Releases 'The Thrill' Video|publisher=[[RTTNews]]|accessdate=October 21, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhODf3GA|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> In an interview for ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Miguel said that he intended to "change urban radio" and "the sound of what's expected from R&B songs on the radio".<ref name="Lipshutz"/> He explained the album's title as "a metaphor for our life; everyone has their own ''Kaleidoscope Dream'', it is the life that they project and it is the life that they are solidifying with their conscious decision and their subconscious feelings."<ref name="Headley"/> He also said that the album represents the fantasies that are conveyed through dreams, which he felt embody "the purest form of fantasy we unleash through our subconscious ... the truest freedom we can experience. Totally unrepressed and totally creative."<ref name="Romero">{{cite web|last=Romero|first=Angie|date=October 4, 2012|url=http://abcnews.go.com/ABC_Univision/Entertainment/rb-singer-miguel-prince-generation/story?id=17399499|title=Album Review: Miguel's Kaleidoscope Dream is Magical|publisher=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhOG9C5N|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref>

== Writing and recording ==
[[File:Alicia Keys @ Tokyo Summer Sonic 2008 01.jpg|right|thumb|190px|[[Alicia Keys]] co-wrote and sang background vocals on "Where's the Fun in Forever".]]

Miguel worked on the album for approximately three months.<ref>{{cite web|last=McKynzie|first=Amber|date=October 19, 2012|url=http://www.sohh.com/2012/10/kaleidoscope_dream.html|title=Kaleidoscope Dream: "I Was Still Being Experimental & Creative."|publisher=[[SOHH]]|accessdate=October 26, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhOaHzzX|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> He sought to play a larger creative role than he had on ''All I Want Is You'',<ref name="Headley"/> and produced most of ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' and either wrote or co-wrote every song on the album.<ref name="Kellman"/> He said of his creative role on the album in an interview for [[Stereogum]], "It was really important that I was very much involved in creating the sound, pulling in the textures, pulling in the colors. Painting honestly and trying to be as concise and true to what it was I was getting in my head."<ref name="Goble">{{cite web|last=Goble|first=Corban|date=September 27, 2012|url=http://stereogum.com/1162512/miguel-talks-kaleidoscope-dream/video/|title=Miguel Talks Kaleidoscope Dream|publisher=[[Stereogum]]|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQGSAOD|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> He recorded most of the album at [[Platinum Sound Recording Studios]] in New York City and MJP Studios in Los Angeles; the songs "Arch & Point" and "Gravity" were recorded at Gustavo's Golden Gloves Gymnasium in Los Angeles.<ref name="liner">{{cite album-notes|title=Kaleidoscope Dream|artist=[[Miguel (singer)|Miguel]]|publisher=[[RCA Records]]|type=CD liner|publisherid=88725-47203-1}}</ref> Miguel recorded "[[Adorn (song)|Adorn]]" in 2011 in the bedroom of his Los Angeles apartment, which he used as a makeshift studio at the time.<ref name="Cooper">{{cite journal|last=Cooper|first=Duncan|date=November 16, 2012|url=http://www.thefader.com/2012/11/16/miguel-second-wind/#ixzz2CRIXAlvY|title=Miguel: Second Wind|journal=[[The Fader]]|location=New York|issue=83|accessdate=November 17, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6CFacqeii|archivedate=November 17, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Parts of the album were edited by Miguel and his [[Audio engineering|engineers]] using [[Pro Tools]].<ref name="liner"/>

Miguel wanted the album to be "a pure and honest projection of my lifestyle and my kaleidoscope dream", and used the music's pace and sound to represent his lifestyle and his lyrics to represent his personality.<ref name="Goble"/> To sustain his creative approach, Miguel avoided media outlets that he usually visited for music, including radio and Internet blogs.<ref name="Goble"/> He drew on musical influences from early in his life, including [[classic rock]], [[country rock]], and [[funk]], to incorporate [[rock music|rock]] flourishes on the album.<ref name="Goble"/> He also incorporated the [[Roland TR-808]] to give the music a distinct percussive feel.<ref name="Goble"/> He enlisted an orchestra and incorporated string arrangements, along with a [[Loop (music)|drum loop]], to the album's title track, which he felt aurally defined the moods of his personality.<ref name="Thomas">{{cite web|last=Thomas|first=Rebecca|date=October 10, 2012|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1695224/miguel-kaleidoscope-dream-tracks.jhtml|title=Miguel Talks Kaleidoscope Dream, 'Friends' With Benefits: Watch Here!|publisher=[[MTV News]]. [[Viacom]]|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhOr3Art|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Miguel also worked with previous collaborators [[Salaam Remi]] and Nathan "Happy" Perez, among other producers.<ref name="Kellman"/> Recording artist [[Alicia Keys]] sang background vocals on the song "Where's the Fun in Forever", and Brook D'Leau of [[J*Davey]] played keyboards on "Candles in the Sun".<ref name="Kellman"/>

Apart from sexual themes, Miguel wrote about conversational and existential topics.<ref name="Goble"/> When writing "Pussy Is Mine", he drew on his sexual behavior as a [[single person|single]] man and "moments of power and vulnerability" with a sexually active woman.<ref name="Thomas"/> Miguel originally wrote "Where's the Fun in Forever" with Alicia Keys for her 2012 album ''[[Girl on Fire (album)|Girl on Fire]]'' at a recording studio in Jamaica.<ref name="Verse">{{cite web|author=Verse|date=September 18, 2012|url=http://www.soulculture.co.uk/music-blog/miguel-on-alicia-keys-collaboration-wheres-the-fun-in-forever-soulculture-tv/|title=Miguel on Alicia Keys collaboration <U+201C>Where<U+2019>s The Fun In Forever<U+201D>|publisher=SoulCulture|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhOsjNIr|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> He conceived the song while spending time with Keys on the roof of the studio, which he recounted in an interview for [[MTV News]], "I had was this amazing blanket of stars in the sky and the sound of waves in the distance, great vibe ... So here I am trying to be creative for Alicia and it just dawned on me: Well, what if we did live forever? Could we have accomplished all of these amazing things? Would we have come so far? ... Would we have come up with all these theories or built all of these amazing, amazing architectural beautiful things ... or would we have been lazy?"<ref name="Thomas"/> The album's title track was written by Miguel while he was working on ''All I Want Is You''. In reaction to Jive's request for more conventional R&B songs, he composed the song with unusual lyrics and without a [[hook (music)|hook]], chorus, or [[musical form|form]].<ref name="Cooper"/>

== Composition ==
{{Quote box
 |quote = The album's title works: on ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' images and sounds repeat, refract and coalesce ... It's made up of love songs, but they are more specifically songs arguing for love, acting casual, wishing and hoping and then imagining what it would be like to consummate. Early days and misadventures. It's soul-baring, but mirrored and fairly guarded.
 |source = <U+2014> Frannie Kelley, [[NPR]]<ref name="Kelley"/>
 |quoted = true
 |bgcolor = #FFFFF0
 |salign = center
 |align = right
 |width = 29%
 |border = 1px
 |fontsize = 90%
}}
An idiosyncratic album,<ref>{{cite news|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=October 11, 2012|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2012-10-11/music/miguel_kaleidoscope_dream_r_and_b/|title=Miguel Finds His Place|newspaper=[[LA Weekly]]|accessdate=October 25, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhOwhgiy|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' features sparse production,<ref name="Larson">{{cite web|last=Larson|first=Jeremy D.|date=October 5, 2012|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/10/album-review-miguel-kaleidoscope-dream/|title=Album Review: Miguel <U+2013> Kaleidoscope Dream|publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=October 20, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhP0HcZs|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> eccentric details,<ref name="Kot">{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|date=October 12, 2012|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/turnitup/chi-miguel-album-review-kaleidoscope-dream-reviewed-20121012,0,1158753.column|title=Album review: Miguel, 'Kaleidoscope Dream'|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=October 19, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BXjGs6JC|archivedate=October 19, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> thick [[bass line]]s,<ref name="Cooper"/> buzzing [[synthesizer]]s,<ref name="Kennedy"/> and hazy, [[reverberation|reverbed]] sounds.<ref name="Johnston"/> [[Allmusic]]'s Andy Kellman finds the album "funkier and weirder" than ''All I Want Is You'' and observes an "illusory atmosphere ... intensified by some unexpected touches".<ref name="Kellman">{{cite web|last=Kellman|first=Andy|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/kaleidoscope-dream-mw0002413681|title=Kaleidoscope Dream - Miguel|publisher=[[Allmusic]]. [[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=October 8, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhO6oxaI|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Stylistically, its music is characterized by [[electronic music|electronic]] flourishes,<ref name="Capobianco">{{cite news|last=Capobianco|first=Ken|date=October 2, 2012|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2012/10/01/review-miguel-kaleidoscope-dream/4oiBSgRFDvhGDMeCJEq9VK/story.html|title=CD Review: Miguel, <U+2018>Kaleidoscope Dream<U+2019>|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=October 20, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhP4W8rQ|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> [[Psychedelic music|psychedelic]] [[Texture (music)|textures]], and [[funk rock]] guitar.<ref name="Rytlewski"/> Miguel sings with expressive [[falsetto]] and [[tenor]] registers on the album.<ref name="Larson"/><ref name="Capobianco"/> Alfred Soto of [[The Quietus]] observes a "joy" in his singing that "leavens the often brooding nature" of the music.<ref name="Soto">{{cite web|last=Soto|first=Alfred|date=October 16, 2012|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/10378-miguel-kaleidoscope-dream-review|title=Miguel|publisher=[[The Quietus]]|accessdate=October 20, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPLxHAI|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref>

As an R&B album, ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' deviates from genre conventions by minimizing the influence of [[hip hop music|hip hop]],<ref name="Rytlewski"/> and drawing heavily on [[psychedelic rock]] and [[psychedelic pop|pop]] elements.<ref name="DeRogatis">{{cite web|last=DeRogatis|first=Jim|authorlink=Jim DeRogatis|date=October 18, 2012|url=http://www.wbez.org/blogs/jim-derogatis/2012-10/miguel-proves-be-potent-voice-rb-103230|title=Album review: Miguel, 'Kaleidoscope Dream'|publisher=[[WBEZ]]. [[Chicago Public Media]]|accessdate=October 26, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BiSJ2sUz|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Music writers compare the album's style to [[Prince (musician)|Prince]],<ref name="Romero"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Howard|first=Jackson|date=October 2, 2012|url=http://www.michigandaily.com/arts/miguel-review|title=Getting down and dirty with Miguel's kaleidescopic sophomore album|newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]]|location=Ann Arbor|accessdate=October 28, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BlUHziUt|archivedate=October 28, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> particularly his mid-1980s works such as "[[Darling Nikki]]" (1983) and ''[[Around the World in a Day]]'' (1986).<ref name="DeRogatis"/><ref name="Browne">{{cite web|last=Browne|first=Rembert|date=October 5, 2012|url=http://www.grantland.com/blog/hollywood-prospectus/post/_/id/59094/miguel|title=Miguel's Kaleidoscope Dream and the R&B Renaissance of 2012|publisher=[[Grantland.com|Grantland]]|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhP95NDM|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Alex Macpherson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' perceives a "headier aesthetic" on ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' than on its predecessor, with the music incorporating "faded psychedelia" and "intimate experiments in ''[[Purple Rain (album)|Purple Rain]]''-esque rock".<ref name="Macpherson">{{cite news|last=Macpherson|first=Alex|date=October 18, 2012|at=section G2, p. 23|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2012/oct/18/miguel-kaleidoscope-dream-review|title=Miguel: Kaleidoscope Dream <U+2013> review|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|accessdate=October 19, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhP5yRQa|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Music journalist [[Maura Johnston]] comments that much of it "sounds, as the title might suggest, [[fractal art|fractal]]."<ref name="Johnston">{{cite journal|last=Johnston|first=Maura|authorlink=Maura Johnston|date=October 1, 2012|url=http://www.spin.com/#reviews/miguel-kaleidoscope-dream-bystormrca|title=Miguel, 'Kaleidoscope Dream' (Bystorm/RCA)|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|accessdate=October 9, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPCrrCm|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref>

The album's lyrics generally deal with themes of adult love, meaningful sex,<ref name="Cooper"/> and romance.<ref name="Rytlewski"/> Andrew Ryce of [[Pitchfork Media]] interprets its "overarching theme" to be "the highly sexualized seen through the lens of the eager and innocent."<ref name="Ryce"/> Miguel's lyrics express modesty,<ref name="Ryce">{{cite web|last=Ryce|first=Andrew|date=October 4, 2012|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/17125-kaleidoscope-dream/|title=Miguel: Kaleidoscope Dream|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|accessdate=October 20, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPEI3ma|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> yearning, vulnerability,<ref name="Cooper"/> and cheeky humor.<ref name="Kelley">{{cite web|last=Kelley|first=Frannie|date=September 23, 2012|url=http://www.npr.org/2012/09/24/161566783/first-listen-miguel-kaleidoscope-dream|title=First Listen: Miguel, 'Kaleidoscope Dream'|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=October 20, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPHNW3B|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> NPR's Frannie Kelley likens his songwriting to [[Tony! Toni! Ton<U+00E9>!]] and notes "[[Little Richard]]-level insinuations" and "absurd provocations in the style of [[Akinyele (rapper)|Akinyele]]".<ref name="Kelley"/> [[Consequence of Sound]]'s Jeremy D. Larson views that he employs a "fangs-out approach to R&B" similar to [[Frank Ocean]] and [[The Weeknd]], writing that "nothing shrouds Miguel and his directives, and worries, and prayers, and cat calls <U+2014> it's all there, full of light and love, refracting through a kaleidoscope of [[Old Fashioned glass|rocks glasses]], rainy windshields, and blood-shot eyes."<ref name="Larson"/> [[Jim DeRogatis]] finds Miguel "man enough to admit his own insecurities and question whether he's worthy of love<U+2014>or lustful indulgence", asserting that on songs such as "Pussy Is Mine" and "How Many Drinks?", he "isn't bragging but either wishing for what he doubts he<U+2019>ll ever achieve or hoping he has what it takes to do so."<ref name="DeRogatis"/>

== Content ==
{{Listen|pos = left
 |filename     = Miguel - Use Me.ogg
 |title        = "Use Me"
 |description  = The ballad about sexual vulnerability features [[Shoegazing|shoegaze]] guitars, oscillating beats, and echo-laden pleas to a lover.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Walters|first=Barry|date=August 22, 2012|url=http://www.spin.com/#articles/frank-ocean-miguel-and-holy-other-usher-in-pbrb-20|title=Frank Ocean, Miguel, and Holy Other Usher in PBR&B 2.0|journal=Spin|location=New York|accessdate=October 28, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BlFeEScw|archivedate=October 28, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Battan|first=Carrie|date=July 31, 2012|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/13969-use-me/|title=Miguel: "Use Me"|publisher=Pitchfork Media|accessdate=October 28, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BlFltIrh|archivedate=October 28, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref>
}}
"[[Adorn (song)|Adorn]]" has both digital and analog sensibilities,<ref name="Kellman"/> and features [[on-beat]] [[sub-bass]] sounds,<ref name="Larson"/> falsetto howls,<ref name="Kellman"/> irregular vocal echoes, obscured synths,<ref name="Johnston"/> and minimal keyboard arrangements.<ref name="McCarthy"/> Its lyrics comprise brazen declarations of affection,<ref name="Kellman"/> including promises of adoration to a female subject,<ref name="Tannenbaum">{{cite journal|last=Tannenbaum|first=Rob|date=October 5, 2012|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/kaleidoscope-dream-20121005|title=Kaleidoscope Dream|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=New York|accessdate=October 19, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPQOAP0|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> and are complemented by Miguel's vocal runs and [[ululation]] during the song's [[coda (music)|coda]].<ref name="Johnston"/> Writers liken "Adorn" to [[Marvin Gaye]]'s 1982 ballad "[[Sexual Healing]]".<ref name="McCarthy"/><ref name="Kellman"/><ref name="Johnston"/> "Don't Look Back" has amplified bass,<ref name="McCarthy"/> bombastic drums, urgent vocals,<ref name="Johnston"/> and grand synthesizer riffs.<ref name="Ryce"/> Rob Markman of [[MTV News]] writes that the song "represents the morning after when the reality of the previous night's efforts creep in."<ref>{{cite web|last=Markman|first=Rob|date=October 2, 2012|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1694839/miguel-kaleidoscope-dream.jhtml|title=Miguel Shatters R&B 'Stereotype' With Kaleidoscope Dream|publisher=MTV News. Viacom|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPUQBOa|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Its closing [[Break (music)|interlude]] has Miguel crooning lyrics from [[The Zombies]]' 1969 song "[[Time of the Season]]" over sentimental synths and musky,<ref name="Kellman"/> psychedelic music.<ref name="Ryce"/> "Use Me" features hollow, electronic sounds,<ref name="Tannenbaum"/> heavily [[multi-track recording|multitracked]] vocals, metronomic rhythms,<ref name="Soto"/> and an [[industrial music|industrial]]ized mix of guitar and percussion.<ref name="McCarthy"/> Its lyrics blur expressions of sexual nerves and gentle dominance,<ref name="Cooper"/> with the narrator instructing his lover how she can toy with him,<ref name="Johnston"/> 

The euphoric,<ref name="Ryce"/> [[pop rock]] song "Do You..." contains [[walking bass]], gentle guitar strumming, [[double-time]] drumming,<ref name="Kelly">{{cite journal|last=Kelly|first=Chris|date=October 4, 2012|url=http://www.factmag.com/2012/10/04/kaleidoscope-dream/|title=Kaleidoscope Dream|journal=[[Fact (United Kingdom magazine)|Fact]]|location=London|accessdate=October 20, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPh14qC|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> arrayed falsetto vocals,<ref name="Johnston"/> and heavy reverb.<ref name="Rytlewski"/> Its lyrics suggest a narcotic tryst and mix ambiable [[wikt:come-on|come-ons]] with drug imagery.<ref name="Macpherson"/><ref name="Johnston"/> Miguel's simple lyrics evoke a romantic relationship: "What about matinee movies, pointless secrets / Midnight summer swims, private beaches / [[rock-paper-scissors|Rock, paper, scissors]]. Wait! Best out of three."<ref name="Cooper"/> The psychedelic title track incorporates synthesizer [[arpeggio]]s, [[minor chord]]s,<ref name="Kelly"/> oscillating blips, fuzzy guitar,<ref name="Cheesman">{{cite web|last=Cheesman|first=Danielle|date=September 10, 2012|url=http://social.entertainment.msn.com/music/blogs/groove-blogpost.aspx?post=a01c720b-6f55-435f-9884-db01c35bb1bb|title=Miguel Previews His "Kaleidoscope Dream" (Again) with "The Air Preview"|publisher=[[MSN Music]]. [[Microsoft]]|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPmHcs1|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> and a bassline [[interpolation (music)|interpolation]] of [[Labi Siffre]]'s 1975 "I Got The".<ref name="Kellman"/> The sample's [[groove (music)|groove]] is played at a different tempo than other instruments on the song.<ref name="Rytlewski"/> The song's lyrics feature [[synesthesia|synesthetic]] imagery ("I taste you, infinite colors"),<ref name="Kelly"/> and a boast by the narrator about kissing his subject's [[third eye]].<ref name="Cheesman"/> "The Thrill" has a sparse bass groove, layered vocals and keyboards,<ref name="Kot"/> a slow tempo, and existential lyrics with [[YOLO (motto)|YOLO]] imagery.<ref name="Johnston"/> "How Many Drinks?" has sardonic,<ref name="Ryce"/> swaggering lyrics and a rap verse by Miguel,<ref name="Johnston"/> who veers between seducer and user: "I've got money, but I don't want to waste my time".<ref name="Kot"/> 

"Where's the Fun in Forever" features atmospheric drum and bass,<ref name="Kellman"/> stark piano chords,<ref name="Kelly"/> an a cappella [[bridge (music)|bridge]],<ref name="Browne"/> and a [[call-and-response]] chorus.<ref name="Johnston"/> Its lyrics celebrate youthful bliss and preach a [[wikt:carpe diem|carpe diem]] philosophy.<ref name="Browne"/><ref name="Macpherson"/> It transitions into the rock song "Arch & Point", which has lascivious lyrics,<ref name="Kelly"/> sexually-charged ballet metaphors,<ref name="Browne"/> and bare [[power pop]] elements.<ref name="Kellman"/> The low-key "Pussy Is Mine" features a high [[vocal range]] by Miguel and a rudimentary [[chord progression]] played on electric guitar.<ref name="Soto"/> It has a stripped, [[Demo (music)|demo]] recording quality.<ref name="Kelly"/> The song is about a vulnerable lover's desire to be a promiscuous woman's sole partner.<ref name="Headley">{{cite web|last=Headley|first=Maxine|month=September|year=2012|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/interview/miguel-september-2012-interview|title=Miguel Interview|publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]]|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPq0eNC|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Its sexually explicit, bawdy lyrics eschew masculine hip hop tropes for feelings of insecurity.<ref name="Kot"/> The song is bookended by background studio chatter.<ref>{{cite web|last=Breihan|first=Tom|date=October 2, 2012|url=http://stereogum.com/1166782/album-of-the-week-miguel-kaleidoscope-dream/news/|title=Album Of The Week: Miguel Kaleidoscope Dream|publisher=Stereogum|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPreuge|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> "Candles in the Sun" is a slow burning,<ref name="Kelly"/> political soul song,<ref name="Caramanica">{{cite news|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|date=October 4, 2012|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/04/arts/music/the-rb-star-miguel-at-bowery-ballroom.html|title=Breaking Into Machismo After Playing It Cool|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|page=C6|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPuMLkH|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> with lyrics that address senseless killings and drug-infested communities,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wete|first=Brad|date=August 21, 2012|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2012/08/interview-miguel-kaleidoscope-dream-alicia-keys-fame|title=Interview: Miguel Talks Upcoming "Kaleidoscope Dream" Album, Working With Alicia Keys, and Wanting More Fame|journal=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|location=New York|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhPzyuyU|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> and question the [[existence of God]] and the motives of governments.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gamboa|first=Glenn|date=September 28, 2012|url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/miguel-s-kaleidoscope-dream-review-a-new-vision-of-r-b-1.4052241|title=Miguel's 'Kaleidoscope Dream' review: a new vision of R&B|newspaper=[[Newsday]]|location=Melville|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQ2XY2z|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Chris Kelly of ''[[Fact (United Kingdom magazine)|Fact]]'' writes that, along with "Adorn", "Candles in the Sun" "bookend[s] the album with another tribute to Marvin Gaye, a la '[[What's Going On (song)|What's Going On]]?'"<ref name="Kelly"/>

== Promotion ==
Miguel marketed the album [[viral marketing|virally]] with a three-volume series of [[extended play|EPs]] entitled ''Art Dealer Chic'',<ref name="Matos">{{cite news|last=Matos|first=Michaelangelo|date=August 8, 2012|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2012-08-08/music/the-next-ep-isode/|title=The Next EP-isode|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQ55qZm|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> which were released as free [[music download|downloads]] during February to April 2012 and previewed songs from the album.<ref name="Kellman"/> He released two more EPs<U+2014>''Kaleidoscope Dream: Water Preview'' on July 31 and ''Kaleidoscope Dream: Air Preview'' on September 11<U+2014><ref name="Shamz">{{cite web|author=Shamz|date=July 27, 2012|url=http://www.okayplayer.com/news/miguel-kaleidoscope-dream-water-preview-ep-stream.html|title=Miguel <U+2013> Kaleidoscope Dream: Water Preview <nowiki>[EP Stream]</nowiki>|publisher=[[Okayplayer]]|accessdate=October 8, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQtKSVI|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> to digital retailers.<ref name="Lipshutz"/> In an interview for ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Miguel felt that the strategy allowed listeners to absorb the songs at his desired pace and called it "a great way for me to reconnect with my peers ... the people that I hang out with<U+2014>that go to the same shows, listen to the same music, read the same blogs, same magazines."<ref name="Matos"/> ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' was first released by RCA in [[LP album|vinyl LP]] format on September 25 to make the deadline for the [[Grammy Awards]]' eligibility period without [[record chart|charting]] prematurely on lower sales.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=September 26, 2012|location=Los Angeles|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/grammys-deadline-spurs-early-vinyl-releases-1007959472.story|title=Grammys Deadline Spurs Early Vinyl Releases From Cher Lloyd, Muse|journal=Billboard|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQ7xrqK|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> The album was also his first to be released in the United Kingdom.<ref name="Batte">{{cite web|last=Batte|first=Elliott|date=October 31, 2012|url=http://www.stereoboard.com/content/view/175665/9|title=American Singer Miguel Lines Up Biggest Headline UK Tour Yet|publisher=Stereoboard UK|accessdate=November 4, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BvNludwO|archivedate=November 4, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref>

The album's [[lead single]] "Adorn" was released on August 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239|title=FMQB: Radio Industry News, Music Industry Updates, Arbitron Ratings, Music News and more!|publisher=Friday Morning Quarterback Album Report|accessdate=October 25, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Bfb5Gvzv|archivedate=October 25, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> It was a sleeper hit on urban radio,<ref name="Kennedy"/> and became Miguel's second number-one single on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]],<ref name="Kellman"/> as well as the highest charting single of his career at number 17 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/miguel/chart-history/1587346|title=Miguel Album & Song Chart History|work=Billboard|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=October 20, 2012}}</ref> By September, the single had sold 190,000 copies.<ref name="Lipshutz"/> "Do You..." was released on September 18 as the second single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/do-you-single/id561312088|title=Do You - Single by Miguel|publisher=[[iTunes Store|iTunes]]. [[Apple Inc.|Apple Inc]]|accessdate=October 27, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BjGlPMkr|archivedate=October 27, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> It reached number 49 on the ''Billboard'' Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/song/miguel/do-you/30583717|title=Do You... - Miguel|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=October 26, 2012}}</ref> Its [[music video]] was released on October 3 and featured tableaus of the [[Great Basin Desert]] and black-and-white shots of Miguel with his girlfriend Nazanin Mandi.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lansky|first=Sam|date=October 3, 2012|url=http://idolator.com/6990111/miguel-do-you-video|title=Miguel<U+2019>s <U+201C>Do You<U+2026><U+201D> Video: Watch The Hypnotic Clip|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]. [[Buzz Media]]|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQCc8RZ|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Miguel performed "Do You..." on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'' on November 16.<ref>{{cite journal|date=November 17, 2012|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/11/17/miguel-performs-do-you-on-late-night-with-jimmy-fallon/|title=Miguel Performs 'Do You' on 'Late Night with Jimmy Fallon'|journal=[[Rap-Up]]|location=Calabasas|accessdate=November 17, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6CFhpLCFY|archivedate=November 17, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> A video for "The Thrill" was also released on October 4.<ref name="RS">{{cite journal|date=October 4, 2012|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/miguel-chases-the-thrill-premiere-20121004|title=Miguel Chases 'The Thrill' <U+2013> Premiere|journal=Rolling Stone|location=New York|accessdate=October 21, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQTcCGs|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> Filmed in black and white with [[fast cutting|fast cut]] editing and montage shots,<ref name="RS"/> it depicted Miguel and his friends at a birthday party for Mandi.<ref name="RTT"/>

Miguel embarked on a short promotional tour in the United States on September 26.<ref name="Lipshutz"/> He also promoted the album with television performances on ''[[106 & Park]]'', ''[[The Wendy Williams Show]]'', ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', and ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]''.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.eurweb.com/2012/09/miguel-set-to-release-sophomore-cd-kaleidoscope-dream-on-tuesday-october-2/|title=Miguel Releases Sophomore CD <U+2018>Kaleidoscope Dream<U+2019> on Tuesday, Oct. 2|publisher=The Chamber Group|location=New York|last1=Archibald|first1=Sherlen|last2=Plotkin|first2=Juliana|accessdate=October 23, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQWCKAL|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> He continued touring in support of the album for six months throughout North America and Europe,<ref name="Lipshutz"/> including dates as a supporting act on [[Trey Songz]]' Chapter V World Tour during November 2012 to February 2013,<ref>{{cite journal|date=October 9, 2012|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/10/09/trey-songz-announces-chapter-v-world-tour-with-miguel-elle-varner/|title=Trey Songz Announces <U+2018>Chapter V World Tour<U+2019> with Miguel, Elle Varner|journal=[[Rap-Up]]|location=Los Angeles|accessdate=October 25, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQaIyxp|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> as well as a headlining tour in the UK and Ireland during January 2013.<ref name="Batte"/> Although his concerts did not involve choreography, Miguel routinely rehearsed in a dance studio and practiced singing in front of a mirror. In concert, he performed dramatic leaps, staggers, and other moves in a fashion similar to Little Richard and [[James Brown]].<ref name="Cooper"/> Duncan Cooper of ''[[The Fader]]'' characterized his shows as "the expression of hard work", observing that "what Miguel lacks in natural grace, he makes up for in crowd-rallying shows of effort ... His breathing slows, he quiets the band, he falls to his knees. Then he roars."<ref name="Cooper"/>

== Reception ==
=== Critical response ===
{{Album ratings
| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]
| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name="Kellman"/>
| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''
| rev2Score = A<U+2013><ref name="Rytlewski"/>
| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''
| rev3Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref name="Kot"/>
| rev4 = [[Consequence of Sound]]
| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="Larson"/>
| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''
| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name="Macpherson"/>
| rev6 = [[Pitchfork Media]]
| rev6Score = 8.4/10<ref name="Ryce"/>
| rev7 = [[PopMatters]]
| rev7Score = 8/10<ref name="McCarthy"/>
| rev8 = [[The Quietus]]
| rev8Score = favorable<ref name="Soto"/>
| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''
| rev9Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name="Tannenbaum"/>
| rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''
| rev10Score = 9/10<ref name="Johnston"/>
}}
''Kaleidoscope Dream'' received rave reviews from contemporary [[music criticism|music critics]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Neasman|first=Brandon|date=October 4, 2012|url=http://thegrio.com/2012/10/04/changing-of-the-guard-how-frank-ocean-miguel-and-more-helped-rb-find-its-soul-again/|title=Changing of the guard: How Frank Ocean, Miguel and more helped R&B find its soul again|work=[[The Grio]]|publisher=[[NBC News]]|accessdate=October 25, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQcnx4c|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 86, which indicates "universal acclaim", based on 14 reviews.<ref name="Metacritic">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/kaleidoscope-dream/miguel|title=Kaleidoscope Dream Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More|publisher=[[Metacritic]]. [[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=October 8, 2012}}</ref> Allmusic editor Andy Kellman cited it as "2012's most pleasurable pop-R&B album" and commented that, although the lyrics occasionally come "too close to 'artsy' teenage erotic poetry," each song has "an attractive quality, whether it's a heavenly melody, a riveting rhythm, or a boggling production nuance."<ref name="Kellman"/> Alex Macpherson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that Miguel's occasional "appeal to [[indie rock|indie]] tropes ... is balanced by genuinely thoughtful songwriting" and commended him for using his previous commercial breakthrough "as a springboard to radically change course".<ref name="Macpherson"/> [[Greg Kot]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' complimented both his "left turns" and references to older influences, writing that Miguel "creates a fluid, dreamscape environment that floats across eras with a connoisseur's discerning feel for the telling detail."<ref name="Kot"/> 

Rob Tannenbaum of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' commented that "Miguel proves that he is, easily, uninhibited enough to inherit the tradition of eccentric R&B freakiness handed down from Marvin Gaye to Prince to [[R. Kelly]]."<ref name="Tannenbaum"/> Evan Rytlewski of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' compared Miguel's "pop instincts" to those of Prince and stated, "Few, if any, of [Miguel's] contemporaries have demonstrated this much control over their aesthetic."<ref name="Rytlewski"/> Maura Johnston of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' praised Miguel's "command" of his "impeccable songwriting chops" and "deceptively supple voice", and called the album "startling and invigorating, a fully formed statement from an artist hungrily surging toward the front of pop music's creative pack."<ref name="Johnston"/> Sean McCarthy of [[PopMatters]] called it a "thrilling listen" and viewed that, along with Frank Ocean's ''[[Channel Orange]]'', it "shows that in terms of mainstream music, the trailblazers of 2012 are firmly entrenched in the R&B community."<ref name="McCarthy"/> 

In a mixed review, Ken Capobianco of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' felt that "some tracks are simply [[overproduction (music)|overproduced]]" and found Miguel "too remote for a true soul singer."<ref name="Capobianco"/> Jon Caramanica of ''[[The New York Times]]'' found the album to be "purposefully, a little washed-out, a blend of Prince-isms and slurry grooves", and stated, "Sometimes it's great, sometimes it's on the verge."<ref name="Caramanica"/> Frannie Kelley of [[NPR]] critiqued that the album "requires a few twists to bring Miguel's vision into focus", but commended his effort as a "perfectionist" and found him comparable to "[[Stevie Wonder]], Prince and [[Van Morrison]]."<ref name="Kelley"/> Pitchfork Media's Andrew Ryce found the album to be "respectful of tradition, quietly ambitious, and deeply personal", and cited Miguel as "the rare vocalist who makes you ''feel'' what he's singing about, even when his lyrics can be transparent."<ref name="Ryce"/> Alfred Soto of The Quietus was pleasantly surprised by "the range of sonic ideas, fully realized songs, and prodigious vocal talent" by Miguel after a "tentative" debut and commented that he "articulates how a love man can be louche without being a douche."<ref name="Soto"/>

=== Commercial performance ===
The album debuted at number three on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 71,000 copies in its first week.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=October 10, 2012|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/muse-s-the-2nd-law-leads-seven-top-10-debuts-1007975762.story|title=Muse's 'The 2nd Law' Leads Seven Top 10 Debuts on Billboard 200|journal=Billboard|location=Los Angeles|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQhHusp|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> It sold 30,000 copies in its second week on the chart.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ramirez|first=Rauly|date=October 18, 2012|url=http://www.billboard.com/column/the-juice/chart-juice-mgk-s-lace-up-debuts-at-no-2-1007985602.story|title=Chart Juice: MGK's 'Lace Up' Debuts at No. 2 on R&B/Hip-Hop Albums Chart|journal=Billboard|location=New York|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQk02Ij|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> As of November 14, 2012, ''Kaleidoscope Dream'' has sold 169,600 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|last=Langhorne|first=Cyrus|date=November 14, 2012|url=http://www.sohh.com/2012/11/ne-yo_paints_top_5_red_meek_mill_wakes_u.html|title=Ne-Yo Paints Top 5 R.E.D., Meek Mill's Dream Wakes Up At No. 8, Too $hort, E-40 & Saigon Invade The Chart|publisher=SOHH|accessdate=November 14, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6CBP5Dr5k|archivedate=November 14, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, the album charted for three weeks on the [[UK R&B Chart]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/r-and-b-albums-chart/|title=R&B Albums Top 40 - 27th October 2012|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BfVrhdxR|archivedate=October 24, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref> on which it peaked at number 13.<ref name="UKR&B">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/2012-10-13/|title=2012-10-13 Top 40 Official UK Albums Archive|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=October 24, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6BhQo38tj|archivedate=October 26, 2012|deadurl=no}}</ref>

